Every Thursday night I thoroughly enjoy my #MLIS #LIS620 with Dr Velez. She is so amazing. TIL that I've been thinking about "Brave Spaces" not "Safe Spaces".

Of course group work doesn’t fall into this as you need to ensure your pieces are ready for others to work with, but I felt such relief when I knew I could submit some pieces on time and others late if need be. 

#studentadvocacy

Adding to all this, for me anyways, is I am currently in 2 #MLIS courses and both profs stated clearly from the outset that late work would not be penalized. One even said if we get a grade we don’t like, we can submit as many times as we’d like. 

#studentadvocacy

I need to add that this is all well intentioned work, but most of the time it comes from a specific world view that portends care yet has blind spots. As a huge Merleau-Ponty fan, I’m all about those blind spots and I know I have many myself. 

#studentadvocacy

What I’m writing about RN comes from years of following student voices and their advocates. I could write a LONG thread about the work that has brought me to this point of feeling so passionate about #STUsvoice 

#studentadvocacy

STU also points out that most people who advocate for themselves are white dudes (and I’m guilty of this) who already have power on their side. Ultimately we should never side with power (HT @hypervisible for that thought bomb a while back...) 

#studentadvocacy

STU said that most people who struggle with late work are often not neurotypical and they DMed me because they want future students to not have to go through the struggles they’ve gone through in their degree.

#studentadvocacy

As pedagogues, we are already in a position of power and we should not strengthen the inequities students already feel in classrooms. STU said when they see statements like this one they (and others) would not engage with the prof.

#studentadvocacy

So I started this thread a while ago and, at the bequest of a student (STU) in my DMs, I feel I need to push further from their perspective. To summate: asking students to further advocate for themselves is not a good look.

#studentadvocacy
